07948nam a22009495i 9780226377582DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015048963  a9780226377582  a(DE-B1597)524554  a(OCoLC)957998297  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQE721.2.E85bS64 2016 4aQE721.2.E85bS64 2017 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a576.8622300aSpecies and Speciation in the Fossil Record /ced. by Margaret M. Yacobucci, Warren D. Allmon. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b56 halftones, 26 line drawings, 12 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Taking Fossil Species Seriously -- tChapter One. The “Species Concept” and the Beginnings of Paleobiology -- tChapter Two. The Species Problem: Concepts, Conflicts, and Patterns Preserved in the Fossil Record -- tChapter Three. Studying Species in the Fossil Record: A Review and Recommendations for a More Unified Approach -- tChapter Four. The Stages of Speciation: A Stepwise Framework for Analysis of Speciation in the Fossil Record -- tChapter Five. Morphology and Molecules: An Integrated Comparison of Phenotypic and Genetic Rates of Evolution -- tChapter Six. Fitting Ancestral Age-Dependent Speciation Models to Fossil Data -- tChapter Seven. Contrasting Patterns of Speciation in Reef Corals and Their Relationship to Population Connectivity -- tChapter Eight. Towards a Model for Speciation in Ammonoids -- tChapter Nine. Species of Decapoda (Crustacea) in the Fossil Record: Patterns, Problems, and Progress -- tChapter Ten. Fossil Species as Data: A Perspective from Echinoderms -- tChapter Eleven. Species and the Fossil Record of Fishes -- tChapter Twelve. The Impact of Invasive Species on Speciation: Lessons from the Fossil Record -- tChapter Thirteen. Fossil Species Lineages and Their Defining Traits: Taxonomic “Usefulness” and Evolutionary Modes -- tChapter Fourteen. Geographic Clines, Chronoclines, and the Fossil Record: Implications for Speciation Theory -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the species is one of the fundamental units of biological classification, there is remarkably little consensus among biologists about what defines a species, even within distinct sub-disciplines. The literature of paleobiology, in particular, is littered with qualifiers and cautions about applying the term to the fossil record or equating such species with those recognized among living organisms. In Species and Speciation in the Fossil Record, experts in the field examine how they conceive of species of fossil animals and consider the implications these different approaches have for thinking about species in the context of macroevolution. After outlining views of the Modern Synthesis of evolutionary disciplines and detailing the development within paleobiology of quantitative methods for documenting and analyzing variation within fossil assemblages, contributors explore the challenges of recognizing and defining species from fossil specimens—and offer potential solutions. Addressing both the tempo and mode of speciation over time, they show how with careful interpretation and a clear species concept, fossil species may be sufficiently robust for meaningful paleobiological analyses. Indeed, they demonstrate that the species concept, if more refined, could unearth a wealth of information about the interplay between species origins and extinctions, between local and global climate change, and greatly deepen our understanding of the evolution of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEvolution (Biology) 0aEvolution (Biology). 0a